### Footnotes

<span id="fn_385"></span>[70:1](htg13.htm#fr_385.md) A name of the Devī as
She who bestows food, whose sincere devotee will never want rice. In one
hand She holds a rice-bowl, and in another a spoon for stirring the
boiled rice.

<span id="fn_386"></span>[70:2](htg13.htm#fr_386.md) P. 570.

<span id="fn_387"></span>[70:3](htg13.htm#fr_387.md) Śivé.

<span id="fn_388"></span>[70:4](htg13.htm#fr_388.md) All forms of the Devī,
as also the forms of all *Devatā*, whether in the strict sense *avatāra*
or not, are māyik, but to the worshipper none the less real.

<span id="fn_389"></span>[70:5](htg13.htm#fr_389.md) Feminine of Maheśvara,
a title of Śiva as great Lord and Ruler of the worlds.

<span id="fn_390"></span>[70:6](htg13.htm#fr_390.md) *Annapūrṇé
namostute*--the refrain.

<span id="fn_391"></span>[71:1](htg13.htm#fr_391.md) The Devī as She who
yields and is yet Herself unaffected by *māyā*.

<span id="fn_392"></span>[71:2](htg13.htm#fr_392.md) *Dharmaputī*--that is,
a wife married with religious rites. There are other forms of marriage.

<span id="fn_393"></span>[71:3](htg13.htm#fr_393.md) Śiva.

<span id="fn_394"></span>[71:4](htg13.htm#fr_394.md) *Devas*.

<span id="fn_395"></span>[71:5](htg13.htm#fr_397.md) As is Śiva.

<span id="fn_396"></span>[71:6](htg13.htm#fr_396.md) *Annadānaratā*, or
food generally.

<span id="fn_397"></span>[71:7](htg13.htm#fr_398.md) *Sādhakas*, those who
practise *sādhanam* (see *Introduction To Tantra Śāstra*)

<span id="fn_398"></span>[71:8](htg13.htm#fr_399.md) *Kucabhārānate* (see
Introduction).

<span id="fn_399"></span>[72:1](htg13.htm#fr_400.md) That is, the
*svādhishṭhāna padma*.

<span id="fn_400"></span>[72:2](htg13.htm#fr_401.md) *Sharangayuvatīmaye*,
which equals *sharangaśaktisvarūpe*. The sixfold *śaktis* are:
*Hṛdayānga śakti*, *śirongga śakti*, *śikhānga śakti*, *netrānga śakti*,
*avachānga śakti*, and *astrānga śakti* which refer to the *Tāntrika
nyāsa*, done on the heart, head, crownlock, eyes, the body, and the
concluding gesture with the palms of the hands, accompanied by the
*astra bīja* or "*phat*."

<span id="fn_401"></span>[72:3](htg13.htm#fr_402.md) That is, Indrāṇi,
Kaumāri, and other Mātrikas.

<span id="fn_402"></span>[72:4](htg13.htm#fr_403.md) *Sāmrājya*.

<span id="fn_403"></span>[72:5](htg13.htm#fr_404.md) *Sarvānandakare*.
Sarva is one of the eight forms (*aṣṭamūrti*) of Śiva; or it may
literally mean "giver of delight to all."

<span id="fn_404"></span>[73:1](htg13.htm#fr_405.md) This is the *phala*
(fruit or result) portion of the *stotra*. All devotional works contain
a *phala* chapter or verse, which states the result or reward (*phala*)
to be obtained by their perusal, recitation, or hearing. If any
worshipper invokes Devī by any particular name, such as Armada, he
obtains the corresponding fruit. So the Sūta Samhitā (iv, 33, 29, 30)
says: "All names arc attributed by His own *māyā* to Brahman, yet some
apply specially by the wish of Śiva Himself. O sages! by the repetition
of such names one becomes the supreme Lord Himself and before His lotus
face Śadāśiva dances with His Spouse" (see Bhāskararāya Commentary,
Introduction to second Chapter of the Lalitāsahasranāma).

<span id="fn_405"></span>[73:2](htg13.htm#fr_406.md) Devī of prosperity and
wealth.

<span id="fn_406"></span>[73:3](htg13.htm#fr_407.md) Literally, "made
*japa* of"

